/**
 * Content bank for the เติมคำในช่องว่าง · ไวยากรณ์ lesson (see grammar-fitb.ts).
 *
 * FLAT list — every exercise carries its own `topic` (which grammar point it
 * teaches) and `difficulty` (which level it belongs to). The runner mixes ALL
 * topics together within a level; it does NOT group by topic. This is intentional:
 * a level's exercise pool interleaves present tense, past tense, present perfect,
 * passive voice, adverbs, and transitions so learners practice recognizing which
 * rule applies from context, exactly like the real DET Fill-in-the-Blank exam.
 *
 * Passages are short academic/informational articles (scientific facts, history,
 * how-things-are-made processes, animal behavior, argumentative essays) — NOT
 * mundane daily-routine scenes — with vocabulary scaled to CEFR level (easy=B1,
 * medium=B2, hard=C1, see GRAMMAR_DIFFICULTY_META).
 *
 * ~600 exercises: 6 topics × 3 levels × 33-34 each (>=30 minimum per the content
 * brief). Bulk-authored in parallel batches (18 agents, one per topic+level pair),
 * then merged + validated + deduped by a scratchpad script — see
 * project_grammar_fitb_lesson memory for the pipeline.
 *
 * AUTHORING RULES (checked by the scratchpad validator):
 *  - Every passage must contain exactly the markers [BLANK 1] … [BLANK 5], in order.
 *  - blanks[i].correctWord is the word that goes in [BLANK i+1].
 *  - prefixLength must be >= 1 and strictly less than correctWord.length.
 *  - Every exercise id and titleEn must be globally unique.
 *  - Avoid reusing the same content-bearing blank word (main verbs, adverbs,
 *    connectors) across exercises within the SAME difficulty level — closed-class
 *    function words (is/are/was/were/has/have/do/does/did, standard transition
 *    connectors, frequency adverbs) are exempt since they cannot be avoided at volume.
 */
